"The site is open Jan and Feb.  Over 300,000,000 BAHT is raised during this time from donations and transportation fees."

"Available to any religion for prayer. There are 7 monks that are associated with this particular temple. King Ramah 5th donated a personal closet to the temple 100 years ago. They also have an archive written on leaves of the temples history and medical remedies."

"Mr. Likhit is appoint by the community and the Monks to take care of the religious temples and community area. He has overwhelming support from the community for donations and he also handles the financials for the temple. The community decides if they need to improve any facilities in the temple area. The temple has been in exsistence for 33 years and has only had government support one time due to flooding."

"This site would be contributing to the local formal economy, in a somewhat informal manner. Each of the (approx.) 500 vendors have to pay between 30k to 75k Baht to set up their shops. The market is broken up into 4 different sections, the translator could not explain why they were separated. The Deputy monk and his fellow monks collect these fees and use what they need to perform renovations to their three temples. After the  renovations are planned, the rest of the money is given to the local police force, local schools, and hospitals to help with their expenses. There are no "

formal " taxes that go directly to the government from this festival, as they would in America. The festival lasts about 12 days and the calendars dates fluctuate each year because the festival goes by the Lunar Calendar instead of a traditional Gregorian calendar. Lastly, these temples are about 750 years old and were built during the Sukhothai Kingdom."

"We learned a lot about how the people of this area perform ceremonies. We learned that when someone dies, their body is displayed in the casket for up to 7 days and is kept cool by ice. Chrysantymums are a popular flower for funerals because to Buddhists they signify purity. Monks are the religious people that perform the ceremonies and there are long prayers that people sit through and after the "

sermon " is complete they celebrate that persons life and have a large feast. One thing that stood out to our team was that no one was crying or sad. We were informed that in funerals Buddhists' go out of their way NOT to cry because it can affect whether the persons spirit goes to heaven or not."

"The total property area is around 29K acres. This is made up of the Sukhothai section which is around 17K acres, Si Satchanalai section at 11K acres, and Kamphaeng Phet sections at 835 acres. Sukhothai was the political and administrative capital of the first Kingdom of Siam in the 13th and 15th centuries. Si Satchanalai was the spiritual center of the kingdom and the site of numerous temples and Buddhist monasteries. Si Satchanalai was also the center of the all-important ceramic export industry. The third town, Kamphaeng Phet, was located at the kingdom\342\200\231s southern frontier and had important military functions in protecting the kingdom from foreign intruders as well as providing security for the kingdom\342\200\231s extensive trading network."
